# Wazuh Home SOC Lab

## Overview
This project documents the development of a home Security Operations Center (SOC) using Wazuh, Suricata, Kali Linux, and Ubuntu Servers.
The goal of this lab is to simulate real-world cyber attacks, monitor endpoint and network activity, investigate security events, and perform vulnerability assessments 

## Lab Architecture

- Ubuntu Server (Wazuh Manager + Dashboard)
- Kali Linux (Attacker)
- Ubuntu Server (Monitored Endpoint with Wazuh Agent)

## Technologies

- Wazuh SIEM
- Suricata IDS
- Ubuntu Server
- Kali Linux
- Linux
- SSH
- Hydra
- Nmap

## Current Scenarios

- SSH Authentication
- Privilege Escalation
- File Integrity Monitoring
- User Account Creation
- Threat Hunting

## Skills Demonstrated

- SIEM Monitoring
- Threat Hunting
- Endpoint Monitoring
- Network Intrusion Detection
- Linux Administration
- SSH Authentication
- Privilege Escalation Detection
- File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)
- User Account Auditing
- Vulnerability Assessment
- Security Event Investigation 

## Lab Demonstrations

### SSH Authentication Failure and Success

I used Hydra from my Kali Linux VM to target my Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected the repeated failed login attempts and generated authentication alerts, allowing me to 
investigate the activity through the dashboard.

![Hydra Result](Screenshots/Hydra%20result.png) 
![Authentication Failure](Screenshots/Authenticatioin%20failure.png)

### File Integrity Monitoring

To test File Integrity Monitoring, I created, modified, and deleted files on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected each change and generated alerts showing the file activity, 
demonstrating how it can identify unauthorized modifications to monitored files and directories.

![FIM](Screenshots/FIM.png)

---

### Network Reconnaissance

I performed an Nmap scan from my Kali Linux VM against the Ubuntu agent to simulate reconnaissance activity. Suricata detected the scan and forwarded the alert to Wazuh, 
where I was able to review the event.

![Suricata Nmap](Screenshots/Suricata%20NMAP.png)

---

### Privilege Escalation

I simulated privilege escalation by using `sudo` to elevate my privileges on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected the successful elevation to the root account and generated a security event 

![Privilege Escalation](Screenshots/Privelge%20Escalation%20to%20Root.png)

---

### User Account Creation

To alert account management activity, I created and removed a local Linux user on the Ubuntu agent. Wazuh detected both actions and logged the events, demonstrating its ability to monitor changes to user accounts.

![User Creation and Removal](Screenshots/User%20creation%20and%20removal.png)

# What I Learned

Building this lab gave me a much better understanding of how a SOC operates and how security analysts investigate alerts. Before building it, I had learned about SIEMs and threat detection through coursework and labs, but this project gave me the opportunity to put those concepts into practice.
Throughout the lab, I configured Wazuh, integrated Suricata, simulated attacks from a Kali Linux VM, and investigated the resulting alerts through the Wazuh Dashboard. Working through each scenario helped me better understand how different types of attacker activity appear from a defender's perspective.
This project also strengthened my Linux skills by giving me hands-on experience managing users, monitoring file changes, working with system services, and troubleshooting security tools. Overall, it helped me become more comfortable using security monitoring tools and reinforced the importance of investigating events instead of simply generating alerts.
